1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
This is not a map of ships carrying diseases from one place to another.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:24,000
It is a map of ships as disease environments.

3
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:45,000
A ship was a ration system, a waste system, an air system, a medical system, a labor system, and sometimes a machine of violence.

4
00:00:45,000 --> 00:01:03,000
The pirate network is a useful place to begin because it makes infrastructure visible.

5
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Nassau, Port Royal, Tortuga, and the Carolina coast were connected by ships, repair, provisioning, recruitment, capture, resale, rumor, water, food, wounds, insects, and waiting.

6
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:45,000
The point is not that pirates uniquely caused epidemics. The point is that ports were ecological machinery.

7
00:01:45,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Yellow fever and malaria move the story to the warmer edge of the map, where port ecology and vector ecology overlap.

8
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Ships moved people, cargo, and exposure, but the disease cycle still depended on climate, stored water, mosquito habitat, labor, immunity, and timing.

9
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:55,000
A route is not a magic line of causation. It is a way of seeing how local ecologies became connected.

10
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:18,000
Then the map moves inward, into the ship. Scurvy is time made biological.

11
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:48,000
Flux and typhoid belong to food and water systems: casks, storage, handling, drinking water, dirty hands, waste boundaries, and the galley.

12
00:03:48,000 --> 00:04:20,000
The exposure route is not only across the ocean. It is through the barrel, the berth, and the hand.

13
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:48,000
Crowding changes the disease world again. Ship fever, smallpox, and measles turn berths, clothing, bedding, ventilation, and quarantine into epidemiologic objects.

14
00:04:48,000 --> 00:05:20,000
Below deck is not just scenery. It is the architecture of transmission.

15
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:55,000
When the ship reached land, exposure entered quarantine stations, port inspections, hospitals, and politics.

16
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Maritime disease ecology cannot be separated from violence.

17
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Wounds, dirty tools, delayed care, and forced confinement make infection a social fact.

18
00:06:50,000 --> 00:07:20,000
The Middle Passage exposes what maritime movement could become when commerce, coercion, captivity, dehydration, crowding, violence, and disease were fused.

19
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:45,000
The sea did not merely connect outbreaks. It made disease ecological, political, and visible.

20
00:07:45,000 --> 00:08:10,000
The full source-backed exhibit is linked below. The map is not the answer. It is the reading surface.
